        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Assume n ≥ 3 for the moment. We write the permutations it counted by Pn as sequences п (1), п (2),..., (n). Let Un be the number of permutations counted by Pn that end with n - 1, n; let Vn be the number ending in n,n - 1; let W, be the number starting with n - 1 and ending in n - 2,n; let In be the number ending in n - 2, n but not starting with n - 1; and let Sn be the number which has n - 1,n consecutively in that order, but not at the beginning or end. It is clear that every permutation i counted by Pn either lies in exactly one of the sets counted by Un, Vn, Wn, In, Sn, or is the reverse of such a permutation. Therefore",
        "bbox": [
